American-style favoritism capitalism
Do you remember the East Asia crisis? When the American Ministry of Finance and its IMF allies blamed the problems of this region on favoritism capitalism, lack of transparency, and an inefficient government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their companies.
Never mind that under the guidance of their own entrepreneurs, East Asia developed faster than any other region—and with greater stability—over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives a new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "Only a perfect person can criticize another."
Enron used large-scale accounting gimmicks and complicated financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to gain influence and power, shape US energy policy, and avoid regulations.
Favoritism capitalism is not new, nor is it the domain of one party alone.
The former US Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, allegedly tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
Lorsqu'il était en exercice, il était intervenu lorsque le bureau de définition de normes de comptabilité, soi-disant indépendant, a tenté de nettoyer la comptabilité des affaires à prime des cadres supérieurs.
C'est en partie grâce à lui que cet effort pour rendre la comptabilité des entreprises plus transparente a été entravé.
L'enthousiasme de l'Amérique à renflouer les compagnies aériennes avec plusieurs milliards de dollars ou à créer des cartels pour protéger ses industries d'acier et d'aluminium suggère que l'idéologie du marché libre n'est qu'un mince paravent pour le bien-être des anciennes entreprises : donner à ceux qui ont les bonnes relations.
Pour certains, le fait qu'Enron n'a pas été renflouée et que les problèmes n'ont pas été révélés témoigne de l'absence de capitalisme de favoritisme.
Mon interprétation est différente : cela témoigne de l'importance d'une presse libre qui peut ne pas stopper les abus mais peut les réduire.
When the press began to investigate Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
Campaign contributions were not just a matter of public interest, but an investment.
Like most of Enron's investments, everything seemed fine in the short term, but did not pay off in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some relate to politics: the Enron scandal reinforces the case for campaign finance reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by business interests that can in fact buy elections.
The Bush administration refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of business interests in the definition of its energy policy.
Other lessons pertain to economics, particularly the economy of information.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals aimed at efficiently allocating resources to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present the rosiest picture possible.
Accountability is meant to limit potential abuses.
But who will keep the keepers in check?
Who will control the controllers of accounts?
We count greatly on motivations.
Accountants want to maintain their reputation.
But there are other corrupting incentives in the relationship between consulting and accounting controls: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within the accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of the controls could be compromised.
He is perhaps the unknown hero of the debacle.
But the accounting firms and their corporate clients – which is not surprising given the collusion that has developed – have fiercely attacked Levitt's proposal to separate consulting and accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood – and what the Enron debacle has so clearly shown – is that while motivations are important, unregulated markets cannot provide the best motivations on their own.
Markets cannot provide motivations for creating wealth; they can provide motivations for the kinds of schemes that Enron implemented.
The new economy - and its complex new financial instruments - highlight the problems with reliable accounting control structures; they make it easier to complicate them.
Rather than confront these issues, American business turns away from them systematically, supported and encouraged by American-style favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time is finding the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will assert that Enron was an exception: that its collapse was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who break these laws will face consequences and will.
But the vast majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its accountants declare that its central practices obeyed the law and that thousands of companies act similarly.
They are right - and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received reflects sufficient economic reality of a company.
In the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility to be offered these guarantees at the present time.
We need better norms and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people in the world find nothing wrong with the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we see that they can manage them for their own interests.
<s>Mais même lorsque les preuves de ce type d'abus deviennent évidentes, de nouveaux lieux d'abus sont créés à maintes reprises - prenez l'abrogation américaine du Glass Steagall Act, qui a séparé le commercial des investissements.
<s>Nous avons à plusieurs reprises constaté les conséquences des excès de la libération des marchés non entravés.
<s>Nous devons désormais résister à la tentation de nous pencher vers l'autre extrême.
<s>Le défi à relever consiste à obtenir le juste équilibre.
